\description{
Builds an evidence-first ecological interpretation table for checking
whether taxa make sense in an expected environment, habitat, and region.
By default, \code{prompt_only = TRUE} returns the deterministic evidence-first
table, writes a manual-review prompt to a \code{.txt} file, and does not call an
LLM. The normal LLM-backed workflow is \code{prompt_only = FALSE} with an ellmer
chat object supplied via \code{chat}. Externally generated structured results can
be integrated with \code{llm_result} or \code{apply_flag_taxa_llm_result()};
\code{mock_llm_result} remains available for tests and backward compatibility.
}
\section{Taxon evidence table}{

\code{taxon_evidence} can be used to provide curated or previously fetched
evidence that should be considered before any future online evidence lookup.
The manual workflow is to call \code{extract_taxa_for_evidence()}, then
\code{fetch_worms_evidence()}, then pass the result as \code{taxon_evidence}.

The convenience workflow is to set \code{evidence_sources = "worms"}. This performs
the same on-demand WoRMS evidence retrieval internally. Live WoRMS queries
require the suggested \code{worrms} package and depend on external service
availability. For cached workflows, call \code{fetch_worms_evidence()} yourself and
pass the resulting table through \code{taxon_evidence}.

Regional checklist evidence, such as a local WoRMS Clarion-Clipperton Zone
taxlist read with \code{read_worms_ccz_evidence()}, can be supplied through
\code{taxon_evidence} or \code{ccz_evidence_path}. Checklist evidence is kept as a
separate row from generic WoRMS evidence so context-specific regional and
deep-sea information remains visible in the prompt.

Before evidence is added to the prompt, \code{flag_taxa()} filters
\code{taxon_evidence} to rows relevant to the unique input query taxa. Evidence
can match exact \code{taxon_name} or \code{accepted_name} values, matching taxon/source
IDs, or lineage columns such as \code{family}, \code{class}, and \code{phylum} for
higher-rank query taxa. Large sets of lineage matches are summarised to avoid
prompt overload. Full references, URLs, source IDs, and coordinates remain in
the evidence object, but the prompt receives compact evidence fields by
default.

LLM assessment is done once per unique highest-resolution taxon with a useful
assignment, not once per duplicated feature/ASV row. \code{flag_taxa()} keeps an
internal feature-to-taxon map and joins taxon-level assessments back to
\code{feature_id} in the final result. The final table includes all original input
feature rows. Features without useful taxonomy are not sent to the LLM; they
are returned as deterministic \code{flag_for_review} rows with
\code{insufficient_taxonomic_resolution} statuses. The compact lineage sent to the
LLM contains available ranks from broadest to most specific, for example
\verb{Phylum=Porifera; Class=Demospongiae; Order=NA; Family=NA; Genus=Plenaster; Species=Plenaster craigi}. Missing useful ranks are represented as \code{NA}.

The prompt stays compact, but the returned table includes richer deterministic
context and provenance columns: \code{expected_environment}, \code{expected_habitat},
\code{expected_region}, \code{lineage}, \code{worms_environment}, \code{evidence_sources}, and
\code{evidence_summary}. Full reference URLs and source identifiers remain in
evidence objects rather than being pasted into the LLM prompt by default.
}

\section{Ecological interpretation columns}{

The final output separates component evidence statuses from user action.
\code{ecological_status} describes ecological fit as \code{compatible}, \code{plausible},
\code{unlikely_resident}, \code{incompatible_resident}, \code{unknown}, or
\code{insufficient_taxonomic_resolution}. \code{occurrence_interpretation} describes
how to interpret the sequence in the sample: \code{expected_resident},
\code{plausible_resident}, \code{possible_transient_or_allochthonous},
\code{possible_contaminant_or_misassignment},
\code{likely_contaminant_or_misassignment}, \code{uncertain}, or \code{not_assessed}.
\code{recommended_action} is one of \code{retain}, \code{flag_for_review},
\code{flag_possible_exclusion}, or \code{exclude}. \code{flag_possible_exclusion} means the
taxon is likely inappropriate for resident-community interpretation but
should not be removed automatically without user review.

Absence of records is not ecological incompatibility. Known ecology or
defining biology can, however, support \code{unlikely_resident} or
\code{incompatible_resident}. For example, photosynthetic taxa in aphotic
deep-sea benthic samples may be resident-incompatible while still plausible
as transported or allochthonous DNA. Potential contamination or taxonomic
misassignment is represented separately from allochthonous DNA.
}

\section{Evidence-first judgement}{

\code{flag_taxa()} first builds a deterministic preliminary judgement from
matched local evidence for each unique query taxon. This is deliberately
conservative: missing evidence, WoRMS no-matches, lookup failures, absent
CCZ rows, absent Scite/tool records, and absent deep-sea records are treated
as uncertainty rather than incompatibility. A taxon with local marine
evidence and an expected marine habitat subtype such as \code{"deep sea"} is not
excluded only because no explicit deep-sea record was found. For broad ranks
above species, lack of habitat or region records normally remains
\code{flag_for_review}, often with \code{mixed_within_rank},
\code{insufficient_taxonomic_resolution},
\code{no_known_habitat_evidence}, \code{possible_likely}, \code{possible_unlikely}, or
\code{unknown}.

\code{judgement_mode = "evidence_only"} returns this preliminary classification
without requiring \code{chat}. Use it for fast conservative screening.
\code{judgement_mode = "llm_flagged"} sends taxa with deterministic
\code{flag_for_review} or \code{flag_possible_exclusion} actions for LLM/manual
escalation. Use \code{"llm_possible_exclusion"} when you only want LLM/tools to
check taxa with a positive ecological concern that may affect exclusion or
resident-community interpretation. Use \code{"llm_missing_evidence"} when local
evidence should be trusted and the LLM should only fill gaps. Use
\code{"llm_all"} for exploratory or audit runs; it is slower and requires careful
interpretation because models can over-read absence of evidence despite
conservative prompts. \code{judgement_mode} selects taxa for LLM/manual
judgement; \code{allow_llm_tools} only controls whether those selected taxa may
use registered tools such as Scite.

\code{expected_habitat_status} includes \code{no_known_habitat_evidence},
\code{possible_likely}, and \code{possible_unlikely}. These values represent missing
or plausibility-level habitat evidence, not positive habitat
incompatibility. \code{exclude} should be used only when explicit positive
evidence demonstrates strong incompatibility, such as species-level local
evidence showing restriction to freshwater/terrestrial environments when the
expected environment is marine. For broad-rank or allochthonous-DNA cases,
prefer \code{flag_possible_exclusion} over \code{exclude}.

\code{prompt_only = TRUE} supports prompt inspection, prompt-size debugging, and
manual/external LLM use when API access is not available. It writes one
\code{.txt} prompt file and returns the evidence-first result table. The prompt
asks the external LLM to create a downloadable JSON file named
\code{flag_taxa_llm_result.json}, with one object for each listed \code{query_id}. If
the interface cannot create a file, it should output only the raw JSON array
so the user can save it. Use \code{apply_flag_taxa_llm_result()} to read and
validate that JSON and merge it into the evidence-first table.
Deterministic rows not selected for LLM/manual judgement are preserved
unchanged and are marked with \code{llm_prompt_selected = FALSE}.

If \code{allow_llm_tools = TRUE}, the prompt tells the LLM that registered tools
may be available through the supplied chat object and may be used only to
gather explicit supporting evidence. With the default
\code{tool_requirement = "required_for_llm"}, every taxon selected by
\code{judgement_mode} for LLM/manual judgement is instructed to use the registered
tool workflow before returning final JSON and to report \code{llm_tool_name},
\code{llm_tool_query}, \code{llm_tool_evidence_summary}, and
\code{llm_tool_references}. If no evidence is found, the tool attempt is recorded
explicitly as missing evidence, not incompatibility. With
\code{tool_requirement = "optional"}, the prompt keeps looser selective tool
guidance for weak, ambiguous, contradictory, flagged, or possible-exclusion
cases.

Tools should be used to find positive evidence, not to prove absence. If
tool evidence does not resolve the case, the result should remain
\code{flag_for_review}. \code{biohelper} does not call
\code{mcptools::mcp_tools()}, read MCP configuration, or depend on Scite; Scite MCP
is only an example of a tool the user may register on an ellmer chat object
before calling \code{flag_taxa()}. Local \code{taxon_evidence} remains the first source
of evidence. If tools are unavailable or no explicit evidence is found, the
result should remain conservative.

When \code{prompt_only = FALSE}, \code{allow_llm_tools = TRUE}, and \code{chat} is supplied,
\code{flag_taxa()} can run an explicit, targeted tool-evidence pass before the
final structured-output judgement. \code{biohelper} still does not configure or
call Scite directly; it only asks the user-supplied ellmer chat object to use
tools that the user already registered. Candidate taxa follow
\code{judgement_mode}: no tools for \code{"evidence_only"}, missing-evidence taxa for
\code{"llm_missing_evidence"}, \code{flag_for_review} and
\code{flag_possible_exclusion} taxa for \code{"llm_flagged"}, only
\code{flag_possible_exclusion} taxa for \code{"llm_possible_exclusion"}, and all
unique taxa for \code{"llm_all"}. Tools are not used for deterministic retain rows
except in \code{"llm_all"}. Tool evidence gathering is batched separately with
\code{tool_batch_size} and may substantially increase runtime. If a required tool
attempt fails or is missing from the LLM result, the default repair path marks
the row with conservative failed/no-evidence tool metadata rather than
allowing fabricated references or stopping the whole run.

When \code{verbose = TRUE}, progress messages report elapsed time and distinguish
original feature rows, feature rows with useful taxonomy, feature rows
returned as not assessed, unique taxa assessed by the LLM, local evidence
rows and coverage, prompt sizes, optional tool-evidence batches, final LLM
calls, and final returned rows.

HTTP 413 errors from an LLM backend indicate that the final judgement prompt
or request payload is too large for the selected model route, not provider
quota. HTTP 429 errors indicate LLM provider request quota/rate limiting; they
do not necessarily mean Scite/tool quota and do not necessarily indicate a
prompt-size problem. Premature EOF, parse errors, or truncated JSON from a
structured-output call usually mean the prompt/output was too large for the
model or output limit. Small model routes, including some GitHub model
routes, can be too constrained for tool-enabled analyses; use a
larger-context model where possible.

Absence of evidence is not evidence of incompatibility. Tool searches that
find no explicit evidence should normally lead to \code{unknown},
\code{no_known_habitat_evidence}, \code{no_distribution_evidence}, and
\code{flag_for_review}, not exclusion. \code{exclude} requires explicit positive
evidence of incompatibility.
Scite or other registered tools are useful for finding explicit supporting
evidence; they should not be used as absence checkers that prove a taxon
cannot occur in a habitat or region. Broad-rank no-record cases should
usually remain \code{flag_for_review}, \code{mixed_within_rank}, or
\code{insufficient_taxonomic_resolution}.

LLM/tool traceability is reported through self-reported structured-output
columns: \code{evidence_basis}, \code{llm_tool_used}, \code{llm_tool_name},
\code{llm_tool_query}, \code{llm_tool_evidence_summary}, and
\code{llm_tool_references}. These columns describe whether the LLM relied on
local evidence, registered tools, both, or conservative reasoning only. When
a tool is used, \code{references} and \code{llm_tool_references} should contain
verifiable titles, short citations, DOIs, or URLs when available; if the tool
returned no usable references, \code{llm_tool_references} should say so
explicitly. AphiaIDs, DOIs, URLs, article titles, author names, and formal
citations must come from matched local evidence or returned tool evidence;
general biological judgement belongs in \code{rationale} and must not be turned
into fabricated references. These columns are distinct from the deterministic local evidence
provenance columns \code{evidence_sources} and \code{evidence_summary}, which summarise
matched \code{taxon_evidence} rows passed into the prompt.

The required columns are: \code{taxon_name}, \code{taxon_rank}, \code{source},
\code{evidence_type}, \code{evidence_summary}, and \code{reference}.

Optional columns are: \code{accepted_name}, \code{accepted_rank}, \code{source_taxon_id},
\code{source_record_id}, \code{environment}, \code{habitat}, \code{region}, \code{locality},
\code{decimal_latitude}, \code{decimal_longitude}, \code{basis_of_record},
\code{occurrence_count}, \code{reference_url}, \code{doi}, \code{checked_at}, \code{kingdom},
\code{phylum}, \code{class}, \code{order}, \code{family}, and \code{genus}.
}

